<h1>@HI{{sugiru}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vmasustem{{}} @EM{{@HI{{sugiru}}}}
<li> @Aistem{{}} @EM{{@HI{{sugiru}}}}
<li> @Anastem{{}} @EM{{@HI{{sugiru}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{sugiru}}}} is an auxiliary that adds the meaning of "too much" or "to excess".
It is usually used to indicate an undesirable state.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{yuube o@KJ{{sake}}wo @KJ{{drink}}mi@EM{{sugimashita}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I drank too much last night.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The "for" in "too ~ for something" is formed by @HI{{ni ha}}.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono @KT{{apa-to}}ha @KJ{{private^accomplished}} ni ha @KJ{{tall}}@EM{{sugimasu}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This apartment is too expensive for us.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@HI{{ii}} combines with @HI{{@EM{{sugiru}}}} to form @HI{{@EM{{yosugiru}}}}.
</p>

<p>
The negative @HI{{nai}} combines with @HI{{@EM{{sugiru}}}} to form @HI{{@EM{{nanasugiru}}}}.
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{sugiru}}}} is an @1D{{}} verb.
</p>

